## 6. Pros & Cons

- Pros
    - Unbelievable grip that does not fade quickly; it has arguably the best durability of any ESN rubber on the market.
    - Highly linear nature gives the player absolute control over the short game and placement.
- Cons
    - Lacks a built-in trampoline effect, making it physically demanding to play with from mid-distance when tired.
    - Can feel overly firm on passive shots, requiring the player to always be active and committed to their strokes.

---

## 7. Recommended Users & Pairings

- Who Should Buy This: Offensive loopers, players who value spin and durability, and players transitioning from Chinese tacky rubbers who want something faster but still linear.
- Who Should Avoid This: Beginners who need the rubber to generate speed for them, or passive blockers who rely on a soft, bouncy sponge.
- Complementary Rubber Pairings (Opposite Side): If using G-1 on the Forehand, pair with Nittaku Fastarc C-1 or Hammond Z2 on the Backhand for a slightly softer, bouncier feel.

---

## 8. Value & Alternatives

- Value Verdict: Outstanding. Given its competitive price and incredibly long lifespan, it offers some of the best value in professional table tennis.
- Similar Alternatives
    - Same Brand: Nittaku Fastarc P-1 (more speed, less spin/arc); Nittaku Fastarc C-1 (softer sponge, easier to use on BH).
    - Rival Brand: Tibhar Evolution MX-P (more bouncy, faster, but less durable); Xiom Vega Pro (similar firmness, slightly less top-end grip); Butterfly Tenergy 05 (more dynamic bounce, higher price).
- Closest Feel Match Summary: Plays like a slightly harder, more linear, and significantly more durable version of Xiom Vega Pro or a non-tacky Rakza Z.

